{"id":"2009.01750","submitter":"Gabriel Mart\\'inez-Pinedo","authors":"Karlheinz Langanke, Gabriel Mart\\'inez-Pinedo, Remco Zegers","title":"Electron capture in stars","comments":"64 pages, 24 figures, Review article submitted to Reports on Progress\n  in Physics","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1361-6633/abf207","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th astro-ph.HE nucl-ex","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Electron captures on nuclei play an essential role for the dynamics of\nseveral astrophysical objects. The capture rate can be derived in perturbation\ntheory where allowed nuclear transitions (Gamow-Teller transitions) dominate,\nexcept at the higher temperatures achieved in core-collapse supernovae where\nalso forbidden transitions contribute significantly to the rates. There has\nbeen decisive progress in recent years in measuring Gamow-Teller (GT) strength\ndistributions using novel experimental techniques based on charge-exchange\nreactions. These measurements provide not only data for the GT distributions of\nground states for many relevant nuclei, but also serve as valuable constraints\nfor nuclear models which are needed to derive the capture rates for the many\nnuclei, for which no data exist yet. In particular models are needed to\nevaluate the stellar capture rates at finite temperatures, where the capture\ncan also occur on excited nuclear states.\n  There has also been significant progress in recent years in the modelling of\nstellar capture rates. This has been made possible by advances in nuclear\nmany-body models as well as in computer soft- and hardware. Specifically to\nderive reliable capture rates for core-collapse supernovae a dedicated strategy\nhas been developed based on a hierarchy of nuclear models specifically adapted\nto the abundant nuclei and astrophysically conditions present at the various\ncollapse conditions.\n  This manuscript reviews the experimental and theoretical progress achieved\nrecently in deriving stellar electron capture rates. It also discusses the\nimpact these improved rates have on the various astrophysical objects.\n(Abridged)\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Sep 2020 15:27:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-07"}
{"id":"2009.01751","submitter":"Vinicius Lima","authors":"Vinicius Lima, Mark Eisen, Konstantinos Gatsis and Alejandro Ribeiro","title":"Model-Free Design of Control Systems over Wireless Fading Channels","comments":"Accepted for publication at Signal Processing","journal-ref":"Signal Processing, Volume 197, 2022, 108540","doi":"10.1016/j.sigpro.2022.108540","report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SP cs.SY eess.SY","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Wireless control systems replace traditional wired communication with\nwireless networks to exchange information between actuators, plants and sensors\nin a control system. The noise in wireless channels renders ideal control\npolicies suboptimal, and their performance is moreover directly dependent on\nthe way in which wireless resources are allocated between control loops. Proper\ndesign of the control policy and the resource allocation policy based on both\nplant states and wireless fading states is then critical to achieve good\nperformance. The resulting problem of co-designing control-aware resource\nallocation policies and communication-aware controllers, however, is\nchallenging due to its infinite dimensionality, existence of system constraints\nand need for explicit knowledge of the plants and wireless network models. To\novercome those challenges, we rely on constrained reinforcement learning\nalgorithms to propose a model-free approach to the design of wireless control\nsystems. We demonstrate the near optimality of control system performance and\nstability using near-universal policy parametrizations and present a practical\nmodel-free algorithm to learn the co-design policy. Numerical experiments show\nthe strong performance of learned policies over baseline solutions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Sep 2020 15:31:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 26 Jul 2021 21:17:32 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 4 Apr 2022 15:51:11 GMT"}],"update_date